Title: Brave New World
Author: Aldous Huxley
My Review:
To say that I despise this book would be an incredible understatement after the horrors I endured reading it in the 10th grade. I will never forgive Huxley for the literary slights I was forced to endure in this novel, some including but not limited to the chapter where it is impossible to understand who is speaking and literally the entire ending of the novel. Also, I find the use of Biblical innuendo a bit exhausting in American literature and expected something different from such a supposedly monumental novel in dystopian fiction.

I am bitter to this day.

---

Update: I am looking to re-read this book in the future, and will add an additional updated review below this one upon reread. It has been over 5 years since I've read this book after all, and I thought I'd give it another chance.

There is a lot to unpack in this book despite its size, and for people with CPTSD, just be prepared for what this book may uncover while reading it.

Believe me, it’ll be rough, but it’ll be worth it in the end.

Title: The Ring of the Nibelung
Author: Richard Wagner
My Review:
This was... not entirely what I expected.

I absolutely loved the first two plays (Rhinegold and Valkyrie) but the latter two were quite disappointing from a gender equality perspective. For example, there was one scene where Brunnhilde stated that now that she lost her virginity, all of her power was lost, and I... I just balked. Seriously? Just, why?!

I should have known that an operatic masterpiece from the mid-1800s wouldn’t be progressive for it’s time, but I had some hope.

Overall a solid masterpiece of work that I don’t regret reading, and provided the background I’ve always wanted to know from reading the graphic novel series by Alex Alice (Siegfried - would highly recommend) from a while back.

P.S. I look forward to seeing the allusions in LOTR to this book and Beowulf when I read it in the near future.

Title: The Haunting of Tram Car 015 (Dead Djinn Universe, #0.3)
Author: P. Djèlí Clark
My Review: Such an engaging story and setting. The author’s writing style and pacing flows incredibly well, and I’m quite excited to read a full novel from him in the future, especially from this world.

I novel that will wring your heart out like a towel and with each tug spill fluids wrought with loss.
It's everything I wished Fahrenheit 451 and 1984 was, but better.

Title: Deep Work: Rules for Focused Success in a Distracted World
Author: Cal Newport
My Review:
Sooo... Although I didn’t hate this (in fact I got some knowledge nuggets out of it that I think will really help my day to day life happenings), I truly think this book should have been a set of blog posts or a short novella. So many of the latter Rule Chapters are bloated, Part 1 seemed unnecessary, and the book as a whole would have benefited from some more editing.

Then again, keep in mind that I am someone that values the economy of language and doesn’t need to be convinced four times or more in a single chapter that working until 5:30 and no later is a good habit to have, if applicable to your life for example. If you need this, well then I would highly recommend this book to you.

Also, and this is a gripe of mine throughout the book, the author finds it pertinent to add some particularly dispensable phrases that really make him come across as a pompous individual (e.f. “Facebook, at best, added one more (arguably quite mediocre) entertainment option to many that already existed” - I don’t even use Facebook, but why write ‘arguably mediocre’? What purpose does this parenthetical statement have?), which is unfortunate given that this book preaches his mantra.

Title: Ice
Author: Anna Kavan
My Review:
Once I realized that this entire novel was a metaphor for addiction (given the author's past), I have to say that the novelty disappeared for me.

I'm just not interested in pursuing this book further, as I'm just not enjoying it. For context, it's a cross between a fever dream and surrealist fiction with a sprinkle of sci-fi mixed in, and I just went into this with different expectations.

Not a bad book, but it's just not for me, unfortunately.

(I got about 49% of the way through before throwing in the towel)

Title: The Name of the Wind (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #1)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review: Rothfuss writes with such a command over words that convinces me to reread passages just to swoon over the music they make. Autumn being my favorite season, I highly enjoyed the imagery he set about in the story. From the beginning I felt intrigued by the main character, and as the story progressed felt engrossed to his and his colleagues stories. I can only look forward to the next book and hope that the series continues in the coming years; write Patrick Rothfuss, because you have a gift.

Title: American Gods
Author: Neil Gaiman
Additional Authors: Dennis Boutsikaris, Daniel Oreskes, Ron McLarty, Sarah Jones
My Review:
Goodness me… This book was truly remarkable.
Perhaps it was the portions I listened to through an audiobook, or perhaps it was the portions I read in my physical copy of the book, but regardless of how it came to happen, this book truly touched me.
As someone who grew up in America, the philosophy of Neil Gaiman that he weaves into the story of this book truly hits home. It’s not about new gods, it’s not about old gods, and it surely isn’t about liking or not liking the main character, Shadow (not that I didn’t like him, because I thought he was extremely interesting); it’s about the message. I feel like in most books, particularly classical literature, you receive a final message after completing the book, a message that can help you in shaping your ideals, whether you agreed with the author’s ideas or not.
In this case I agreed, and I loved how the story unfolded. I wanted to know what would happen next. In fact, after completing the book, I have questions; perhaps they can be answered and perhaps they can’t, but I truly love it when books linger in my memory, when they have a lasting impact. In all honesty, I finished this book a few days ago, but I wanted to wait and gather my thoughts before officially giving a quick review/synopsis of my thoughts on the book.
Despite all of my praise though, this book isn’t for everyone; what took me so long to get through it was the beginning. I found it to be confusing, very confusing in fact, and it wasn’t until the end of the book that I finally understood the significance of the beginning. However, I find this to be the case with a lot of Neil Gaiman’s literary works so I continued onward. Although knowing that Neil Gaiman tends to unveil new secrets as the story progresses got me through the first 200 pages or so, it could be quite bothersome for people who do not have the patience or wish to commit so much time to understanding the book’s contents.

Regardless, I wholly enjoyed this book, and I would highly recommend it to those who are looking for an eye-opening read, are familiar with Neil Gaiman’s work, and aren’t in a time crunch.

Title: Nevernight (The Nevernight Chronicle, #1)
Author: Jay Kristoff
My Review:
One of the few books I've read in a long time that thwarted every prediction I made about upcoming events. Incredibly impressive and I really enjoyed it.

I didn't think this book brought anything new to the genre, but it was a fresh take on things we have read before that was genuinely well done. Also, although the footnotes can be jarring at times, I enjoyed that I didn't have to read them immediately after a sentence; I could get to a good stopping point and go back and read the footnotes that had world-building-related information.

However, do not read the kindle edition; it does not do kindly to this kind of footnote approach, much less any footnote approach at all.

Title: Everything I Never Told You
Author: Celeste Ng
My Review: A depressing book that truly delves into some heavy hitting topics about race, identity, and the importance of communication. I appreciate the craft of this book and what the author ultimately achieved.

Title: We Sold Our Souls
Author: Grady Hendrix
My Review:
Grady Hendrix knows how to craft an enjoyable, wild novel.
I would highly recommend this to literally everyone; this is so much fun.

Title: Bunny
Author: Mona Awad
My Review:
A few positive thoughts:
- I want to read this book again knowing what I know now about the ending.
- It's a masterpiece in the creative arts.
- The lyrical prose is incredible

Unfortunately the second part of the book for me was dreadfully slow and the premise bogged me down as there was a bit of extraneous exposition in the beginning.

Overall a solid book, and one I would recommend for someone looking for a creative writing masterpiece, enjoys the occult, and isn't afraid for a wild ride.

Title: Horrorstör
Author: Grady Hendrix
My Review: An eerie and fun novel playing off of an amazing concept that suffers from a few cheesy/cliched moments. Overall though I really enjoyed this, even though I believe that the nightmares I will face this evening may challenge that idea.

Title: Born a Crime: Stories from a South African Childhood
Author: Trevor Noah
My Review: Absolutely incredible. I feel as though I’ve learned so much from this book. The writing style and delivery was absolutely perfect for the content and I actually laughed at some points. Backstory about me; I do not laugh easily at shows or literature, but this book brought out my emotional range. Impressive indeed; thank you Trevor Noah for telling your story.

Title: Sabrina & Corina: Stories
Author: Kali Fajardo-Anstine
My Review:
Beautiful prose, really heartfelt stories, but I somehow found it difficult to finish. I don't often read short story collections, so perhaps being drawn out of one story to the next drew me out of this book, since I tried to read it in about 3 sittings (the library was going to repossess it and I didn't want to leave the book unfinished).

Despite my rating though, I believe everyone should read this book. This is the kind of book I wish my schools when growing up covered; the stories are incredibly nuanced with recurring themes and memorable stories, and the writing... did I mention the writing? It was quite good.

Title: On a Sunbeam
Author: Tillie Walden
My Review: There are some quality life lesson in here that strummed against the harp that is my cold heart. Not life changing but heartfelt and meaningful nonetheless.

Title: Bygone Badass Broads: 52 Forgotten Women Who Changed the World
Author: Mackenzi Lee
My Review: Overall, an incredibly solid, enjoyable, and eye opening depiction of women who are not well known in the eyes of history. I incredibly enjoyed this, but recognize that the language used throughout the book will not stand the test of time. Other than that though I learned a lot, and would recommend this book to anyone wanting to start reading some nonfiction.

Title: The Ballad of the Sad Café and Other Stories
Author: Carson McCullers
My Review:
This is the kind of book you read before dawn, before soft-kissed rays hit the Earth with a kind of warmth only experienced when holding someone dear to you.

Although I found the first short story in this collection, which the book is aptly named after, not that exciting for the first 50 pages or so, it picked up tremendously afterwards, and the short stories following it kept me engaged as well. The writing style didn't vibe with me at first, but definitely grew on me over time.

Overall, a solid short story collection that leaves you breathless and the beauty of literature.

Title: The One
Author: John Marrs
My Review: This book was tons of fun and was highly suspenseful to the point that I couldn't handle waiting to find out what was next and completed this book in a single day. I enjoyed it overall and would recommend it.

Title: Perfume: The Story of a Murderer
Author: Patrick Süskind
My Review: I don't believe this book was for me, but I would recommend it to anyone who always wanted to follow a murderer with a great sense of smell around France I suppose.

Title: Between the World and Me
Author: Ta-Nehisi Coates
My Review: Absolutely incredible. A challenging book to read prose-wise, but I believe everyone should read this regardless.

Title: Annihilation
Author: Jeff VanderMeer
My Review: What an incredible novel exploring themes of environmental conservation and action in a genre-bending manner. I can’t fault this book on anything; I honestly think it is brilliant in the way it explores these more philosophical topics and also keeps the thrilling aspects of the book intact with the conspiracy subplot and interactions among members of the team. A must read for anyone interested in science fiction who wishes to expand his/her/their mind.

Title: Kid Gloves: Nine Months of Careful Chaos
Author: Lucy Knisley
My Review:
Absolutely heartwarming and heartbreaking at the same time; I cried so much, but I also learned a ton.

In my honest opinion, this book should be a requirement to read in sex Ed courses across the United States.

My Review:
A collection with beautiful prints and descriptive poems, simple and poignant.
For new or prospective poetry readers, I would highly recommend this collection, but if you are a seasoned poetry reader looking for poetic inspiration through inventive form and style, this collection may not be for you. Despite being in the latter category though, I still enjoyed the unique bird poems; It was a great way to start the morning.

Notable Poems: "The Resurrection Birds" (Absolutely Incredible) & "The Courier Bird" (Simple but effective)

Title: It's Not That Deep: Poems
Author: Jessica Moll
My Review:
This is a weird poetry collection, unlike anything I've read to this point, to be frank. It was enjoyable and I particularly liked its liberal use of metaphors as a way to explore relationship dynamics.

However the constant use of "he said" and "she said" in every single poem, was very monotonous, and I wish other methods of incorporating those phrases were used instead of just attaching those phrases at the end of every other line. In my opinion, that would have really strengthened the collection as a whole.

Also, slightly off-topic, I found that the last poem "Tone or Mood" was very heavy-handed in its way it tried to tie all of the poems together and explicitly say 'it's all a metaphor,' just in case someone was confused. Maybe it's just me, but I really don't want to be told things with poetry, so I wish this poem didn't explicitly say that and employed different methods of ending the collection.

Notable Poems: "More or Less" & "That Particular Disease"

Title: The New Wilderness
Author: Diane  Cook
My Review:
If I were an English graduate student deciding what to write my thesis on, this would be the novel.

Can humans and nature coexist?
What happens when humans are placed in a situation where survival is key - how is there "humanity" affected?

The first question is the question I believe the novel tries to address throughout its course, but most of it is spent following a group of people who are exploring a great expanse without knowing truly what is happening in the world outside of theirs, thus giving quite a limited world view; however, this is accompanied by beautiful naturalist descriptions that truly draw you into the novel, and an incredible pacing, especially given how long the chapters are.

This novel does not provide answers though to the question above, but rather approaches both sides of the question and leaves the reader to ponder: is it truly possible? Instead this novel focuses mainly, in my pov, on mother/daughter relationships, and what they entail; what constitutes as a good mother, and how far 'should' a mother go to protect her daughter before sacrificing her own wants/needs, etc.?

Honestly, this is the part of the novel that truly stood out to me, and felt the most fleshed out, while the dystopian setting felt like more of a surrounding thought experiment - one I am still thinking about mind you, because I found it so interesting.

Overall, I'd say this is an interesting novel that is worth the read - it's not perfect by any means, but it is definitely interesting, in a positive way, and I can't wait to read future work by Diane Cook!

My Review:
This book warrants a review, and a stellar one at that.

Vicki Mandell-King's poems about loss and grief left me in tears. Her poems are incredibly accessible despite their specificity towards her life experiences, which is a difficult feat to achieve and the signs of a masterful poet. Some of the ones that truly stood out to me include: Skating Lesson, Obsession, I Always Cry at Weddings, When Both Are Ready, etc.

This book will be one that I'll look back to in the future fondly, and I hope that others will take the plunge and buy the book in order to experience their own emotional journey of a lifetime.

Title: Queenie
Author: Candice Carty-Williams
My Review:
I ended up picking this book up when I saw it was part of the 2020 Women's Prize Longlist, and I am glad I did as it was quite interesting.

Queenie by Candice Carty-Williams challenges the stereotypes of being a black women by following the life of Queenie, a black woman with Jamaican heritage living in London and working in the Journalism industry, who struggles greatly in her everyday life. She has an unhealthy relationship with men, intense anxiety, and more issues that she works through or accepts throughout the course of her journey in the novel. This journey in becoming someone who can accept herself is a slow but powerful journey that will leave an impact on readers willing to overlook some of the books flaws.

While the book's latter half is incredibly impactful, a reader's journey to get there is difficult. The first 50-60% of the book solely discusses Queenie's relationship with men, and her tendency to make what many would consider "wrong" choices time and time again. I believe this focus took up too much of the book, and cutting certain scenes would have helped the pacing of the book overall. Along with that, Queenie suffers a miscarriage at the beginning of the book, and how she feels about that experience isn't really explored until when she seeks therapy (70% of the book), in which it's only mentioned in passing. Another aspect of the book that felt added on as an embellishment was the Black Lives Matter Movement, which is truly a shame because I would have loved to see this aspect more integrated in Queenie's character as it would have really solidified her motives for wanting to enter the journalism industry, and would have just given her character a lot more substance and body; at times she felt a bit flat, as she didn't seem to have any interests, and even the ones she had weren't really explored in the book unfortunately. Also, and more obviously, adding more substance and importance on the Black Lives Matter Movement would have been incredible in shedding more light on the systemic inequality black people face in the UK and US - this novel could have made a larger statement without deviating too much from the main plot I believe.

Some people have criticized how Queenie didn't want to date black men, and I want to explore that a bit more here. In the book, readers are explicitly told that Queenie doesn't date black men because of an experience as a child she had that made her anxious in the company of a black men, and it isn't ever explicitly addressed for the rest of the novel. However, when Queenie described her relationship with Roy, her mother's boyfriend, when she was younger, and how he mentally abused her that clicked with me as to why she would be hesitant to date black men. I truly wonder if this subtext was the author's intent, but I am sticking by it all the same until a better explanation is stated.

On to the explicitly positive things I enjoyed in this novel. I found that the Jamaican elements and slang (KMT) as they added a ton to the narrative, and I felt incredibly invested in Queenie's well-being and the overall plot. Also, this is a very impactful novel that has remained in my thoughts for the past couple months; it is incredibly memorable and thought-provoking.

Overall, although I believe this book tried to achieve too much, I would still recommend it though to people looking for an impactful novel.

Title: Black Orchid Deluxe Edition
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review:
I really enjoyed this graphic novel - it was ethereal and emotionally melancholic in its tone with beautiful visuals.

Black Orchid is searching for meaning in a body she did not expect to possess, and what should she do with this new life at her disposal? What does she want to do?

This resonates with me at this time in my life, and I would recommend giving this novel a try if you believe such a sentiment would resonant with you as well.

Incredibly powerful and impactful - I cried, I fumed, I stared off into the distance in thought. Simple in prose, but incredible in message and substance, this is a book everyone should read.

I do want to add though that this is a very difficult book to read, and I would recommend to anyone going into it to take their time and digest the content at your own pace.

My Review:
I applaud the author for delving into climate change in this book and I recognize this novel's literary merit (as the prose was superb), but I must say that I found it quite forgettable.

I found that it was a chore to get through - for context, this 200 or so page novel took me over 8 hours to complete in total. If anything this novel is a wake up call for me, as it reaffirms that vignette-styled novels simply cannot hold my attention.

I just honestly don't think it is worth the read, as more digestible literature exists in the market that discuss similar topics.

Title: The Deep
Author: Rivers Solomon
Additional Authors: Daveed Diggs, William Hutson, Jonathan Snipes
My Review:
I did not enjoy this book, mainly because the writing and pacing didn't work for me, but I understand its merit and love the message it portrays about intergenerational trauma.

Regardless, I would recommend this book to people who do not care as much about the writing style and enjoy being told a story with an important message.

Title: Forced Out: A Detective's Story of Prejudice and Resilience
Author: Kevin Maxwell

Title: Ella Minnow Pea: A Novel in Letters
Author: Mark Dunn
My Review:
What an incredibly clever book! Overall I learned a multitude of words from it and enjoyed it, despite a few glaring faults:



- The Romance element in the book was unnecessary in my opinion and really didn't add much other than providing an outsider element as the catalyst for the "game" in the book.

- The "game" in book is cute, but doesn't add a sense of urgency (at least for me). For me that was sensation was given by everyone leaving; that provided a greater sense of urgency than the actual plot. So overall, I don't think the game was a good plot device to drive the story, and could have been excluded in my opinion.

- The characters seemed to blend into one another; they weren't very fleshed out, and didn't have distinctive writing styles to individualize each person from one another. Only Amos was a bit fleshed out, and I enjoyed his character for the three/four letters he wrote.

- The ending was tied up in a clean bow, and I believe if the author left it very open ended and still in a totalitarian state, it would have provided a greater impact to the message of the book against totalitarianism and censorship. Perhaps a final act against the people in power... Or if they had her put in jail for the pangram written at the end instead of honoring their part of the bargain. I just don't think the book should have ended happily given the message.



Can you believe despite all my gripes I still enjoyed this book? Haha - I had fun but I think it's only fair that I should acknowledge that certain aspects needed a bit more development in my eyes to make this novel a favorite of mine.

Title: Children of Time (Children of Time, #1)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
This is a masterpiece. The craft of the writing, the feminist point of view & equality driven perspective littered throughout the book, the incredible resolution - *chef's kiss*.
Although this novel starts off a bit slow I can promise that all unfolds itself in time.
Overall, this book was revolutionary in my eyes and I want to read it again.

Title: Women in Science: 50 Fearless Pioneers Who Changed the World
Author: Rachel Ignotofsky
My Review: A timeless book focusing on the facts and promotion of the sciences for young audiences. Not only will young women benefit from this book, but I would dare say people of all ages and backgrounds would as well. The beautiful art and interesting design choices prove to be an effective way to keep the reader engaged and receptive to the information provided in this book, and I would recommend it to anyone wanting to learn more about female scientific figures.

Title: The Wise Man's Fear (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #2)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review: I don't really know how I feel about this book. As always, I love Patrick Rothfuss's writing, but I truly believe that was the sole reason I was able to get through this book, because the plot is very messy, trailing the reader from one tangent to another tangent to another tangent to another tangent to another tangent - and so on. It's a shame, but I fear this book suffered from middle book syndrome, and I don't believe I would recommend it.

Title: The Knife of Never Letting Go (Chaos Walking, #1)
Author: Patrick Ness
My Review: Overall, this book wasn't terrible, but my disdain for the main character prevents me from wanting to continue with the series.

Title: Over the Top: A Raw Journey to Self-Love
Author: Jonathan Van Ness
My Review: A touching memoir that I would only recommend if listened to because Jonathan Van Ness' writing style is very conversational and I suspect it may not translate well onto a page.

Title: A Darker Shade of Magic (Shades of Magic, #1)
Author: V.E. Schwab
My Review: Although I am aware that this book is categorized as Adult Fantasy, I would like to respectfully re-categorize it to YA Fantasy and leave it at that.

Title: The Bell Jar
Author: Sylvia Plath
My Review:
This is an incredibly depressing novel, which is unsurprising given that the author is Sylvia Plath.

Be prepared to feel obliterated after this read.

Title: The Turn of the Key
Author: Ruth Ware
My Review:
This novel was not at all what I expected, and as a result I am very disappointed.

I'm sure others will find it more satisfying if they have prior experience with gothic fiction and thrillers, but I personally can't bring myself to recommend it.

Title: The Foxhole Court (All for the Game, #1)
Author: Nora Sakavic

Title: The Little World of Liz Climo
Author: Liz Climo

Title: The White Book
Author: Han Kang
My Review: I don’t believe this book is the most incredible book of poetry I’ve ever read, but I do believe it was a solid read. I would recommend it if you are trying to cry or just want to feel depressed on a snowy day, because why not.

Title: Radio Silence
Author: Alice Oseman
My Review:
I really liked this book; it was relatable in a way that slightly stung (but in a good way because I am no longer that person) and really embodied the experience of college and discovering yourself and what you want to do in life. The subplots were engaging as well and even though I figured out who February Friday was before it was revealed I was still invested in the story.

The only portion of the book that I had major gripes with was the way it ended and resolved the main conflicts in the novel. These resolutions were almost cartoonish in the way they were addressed which was disappointing and I think a lot of that portion and my feelings toward it had to do with the writing. Issues like the ones discussed in the book aren’t as easily resolved as they made it out to be and I really wish a bit more focus and time was dedicated to the resolution to make it more believable. Not everyone has to have a happy ending if it doesn't make sense in the plot.

Overall though, this is an enjoyable book for those born in the early 200s and late 90s (given the references made) who just want a happy ending.

Title: Everyone's a Aliebn When Ur a Aliebn Too
Author: Jomny Sun
My Review: I wish I read this as a child, but even now reading this made me almost cry. For how simple it is, it is very impactful.

Title: If I Had Your Face
Author: Frances Cha
My Review:
A very depressing novel focusing on the stories of 5 women living in South Korea. It shows in a slightly exaggerated manner the problematic beauty standards and prevalent sexism in South Korean culture. Also it sheds a light on the preferential treatment and social customs of the wealthy in comparison to those living day by day.

I feel conflicted about this novel; on one hand it emotionally affected me and shed light on issues I didn’t know existed, but on the other hand I didn’t feel invested in the story as it progressed.

I will say that some people might be aggravated because this novel lacks a clear goal in regards to plot, but I believe that is intentional. By taking it day-by-day the novel upholds the belief the women in the novel have; that they cannot look to the future when every day they face such challenges and they question whether or not to live or die.

A well crafted book, but perhaps not for everyone. I appreciated it though, and I think people should read it did they are interested.

Title: Ship Breaker (Ship Breaker, #1)
Author: Paolo Bacigalupi
Publisher: Little, Brown Books for Young Readers
My Review: A solid premise with an interesting execution but not very memorable.

Title: A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo
Author: Jill Twiss
My Review: What a short heartwarming tale.

Title: The Picture of Dorian Gray
Author: Oscar Wilde
My Review: A very dense novel that I may need to revisit at a different point of my life. I greatly enjoyed the ending though.

Title: Bloom
Author: Kevin Panetta
My Review: A cute book with steamy kiss scenes but unfortunately not much else.

Title: Dinosaur Empire!: Journey through the Mesozoic Era (Earth Before Us, #1)
Author: Abby Howard
My Review: I wish I had this book when I was a child.

Title: Heartstopper: Volume One (Heartstopper, #1)
Author: Alice Oseman
My Review: I've been following this web comic on Webtoons for a while, and didn't realize until now that I have already read this book given the chapters I've already read on Webtoons. Overall it is an absolutely heartwarmingly cute and realistic story which suffers from no pacing issues, and is everything I wanted from Bloom. There I said it.

Title: The Artist's Way: A Spiritual Path to Higher Creativity
Author: Julia Cameron
My Review:
While I found the first 50% of the book really inspiring - I cried quite a bit - the ending 50% was a bit disappointing as the ending chapters didn't really have interesting and helpful prompts that applied to me personally.

I definitely took away some gems from this book, but I would be wary to recommend it to others.

Title: Bellweather Rhapsody
Author: Kate Racculia
My Review:
I am thoroughly underwhelmed by this novel; immensely in fact. Unfortunately this novel tries to achieve too much, and does none of it particularly well. When it takes 30-minutes or more to even describe a book's plot out loud, perhaps its premise should be revisited.

Overall I wouldn’t recommend it; please look elsewhere for genre-bending fiction done well.

Author: Kelly Sue DeConnick
Additional Authors: Taki Soma, Valentine De Landro, Robert Wilson IV, Cris Peter, Clayton Cowles, Lauren Sankovitch
My Review: I felt lukewarm about this book, which was unfortunate given how excited I was to read it. Slightly disappointed but I appreciate the idea it was going for.

Title: The Wicked + The Divine, Vol. 1: The Faust Act
Author: Kieron Gillen
Additional Authors: Jamie McKelvie, Matt  Wilson, Clayton Cowles
My Review: What a pleasant trip. More please.

Title: Bibliophile: An Illustrated Miscellany
Author: Jane Mount
My Review: Unfortunately the ebook format of this book has ill placed images, but I hope to reread it in the future as a physical copy. The beauty of this book comes in the form of recommendations and artistically rendered book spines, and it should be experienced in its full glory if you can.

Title: What Is a Girl Worth?: My Story of Breaking the Silence and Exposing the Truth about Larry Nassar and USA Gymnastics
Author: Rachael Denhollander
My Review: Although I didn't enjoy the writing style in the first 30% of the book, it grew on me. Overall an absolutely inspiring memoir. Thank you for telling the world your story, and I truly hope justice and true change can come out of this arduous journey for the benefit of survivors in the future.

Title: Your Immaculate Heart
Author: Annmarie O'Connell
My Review:
A unique reimagining of poetry lies within this book; each poems tells a story, in the manner of a traditional tale, but also plans to invoke emotion which is not an easy feat.

It pushes the boundaries on what poetry is in the realm that I know it, but I don't believe it intelligently used all of the poetic devices available to it. Despite this, I encourage others to read this book and come to their own conclusion.

Overall, an inspiring read that raises the question of what constitutes as a poem, but needed a bit more editing.

Standout Poems: "The Old Man Who Knew Me 10 Years Ago" & "The Boy Drags His Doll"

Title: Skim
Author: Mariko Tamaki
My Review: This book's writing was very melodic and entrancing, but its ending was a bit abrupt. While there were quite a few loose ends, I think the subject matter of the book (adolescence and navigating feelings in an uncertain time) made all the sense as to why.

Title: Book Love
Author: Debbie Tung
My Review: Honestly this is a pretty superficial book relying on tropes of people who enjoy books instead of offering different perspectives of different readers. I was just a bit let down as it wasn’t what I expected.

Title: We Are Okay
Author: Nina LaCour
My Review:
This book is a solid emotional, slow-paced book. In craft, although I am not a fan of short simple sentences, I understand their use in this story to show the main character's thoughts.

The ending packed quite a punch, but the first 60% of the book left me wanting more. By the end, I understood it was to garner an emotional connection to the main character and her friend, but it didn't affect me as much as I thought it would.

One day I will read this again.

Title: We Have Always Lived in the Castle
Author: Shirley Jackson
My Review:
If I ever hear the phrase “I am chilled” ever again I will flip out like a gosh-darn pancake. I didn’t think I would find a book I disliked as much as Brave New World, but I was unpleasantly surprised that I did. The main character was insufferable with no growth occurring to her over the course of the novel, and with such stagnant characters and dry writing, I got increasingly aggravated over the course of the novel. For the love of all that is pure Constance, grow a spine!

Overall, a massive disappointment for a classic gothic novel that I thought I would enjoy.

Title: Someone Who Will Love You in All Your Damaged Glory: Stories
Author: Raphael Bob-Waksberg
Additional Authors: Baron Vaughn, James Urbaniak, Kimiko Glenn, Colman Domingo, Natalie Morales, Raul Esparza, Will Brill, Stephanie Beatriz, Emma Galvin, Nicholas Gonzalez
My Review:
This is so painful for me to say but I did not enjoy this collection and expected more.

I appreciate what the author tried to achieve and the creativity imbued into every story, but some stories dragged on for ages, and others were simply too short and I wanted more substance. My favorite story was "A Most Blessed" but everything went downhill from there. The other stories drawled onwards for what seemed like forever or I blinked and they were over just like that and I just felt... apathetic. I felt like the author intended to evoke a particular emotion but all the context clues to that emotion were fleeting or hidden under tons of innuendo.

Sometimes too much is too much.

Title: We Are the Ants
Author: Shaun David Hutchinson
My Review:
This book was heart-wrenching; I'm still thinking about it, feeling for the characters and their respective situations...
Just truly a beautiful and awe-inspiring work, and a great way to start reading in the new year.

Title: This Is How You Lose the Time War
Author: Amal El-Mohtar
My Review:
I did not see this book as a love story, but more of an ode to the lengths we go for the people we care about, no matter the circumstance. At the same time, I feel like someone could look at this book as a literal bridge among cultures; that love transcends war.

Overall this book was a poet's dream; a book riddled with inspiring and beautiful language that tells an interpretable story for whomever reads it.

This book is not perfect; I think it suffered a bit from pacing issues and the like in the middle or so, when things started moving towards love. Also, I believe that the novel would have been more impactful if the relationship between Red and Blue wasn't framed as a love story. Nonetheless, I am incredibly impressed with what this novel has achieved.

Title: Unwind (Unwind, #1)
Author: Neal Shusterman
Publisher: Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers

Title: The Nickel Boys
Author: Colson Whitehead
My Review:
What an astounding work of fiction based on true events. I grew up in Florida and was intrigued by the premise of this novel, but I didn’t realize what an impact it would have on me.

Although the prose is not my preferred style, I just have to say this is an incredible novel shedding light on a place not known to many to have existed. Also I enjoyed that the emotional impact occurred as a slow burn due to the non-gratuitous depictions of violence; it is truly refreshing to see in a premise that could have easily added such embellishments.

The ending broke me down and I wept silently under the weight of this novel’s words; the epilogue increased the speed of those tears.

Truly a novel deserving of the Pulitzer Prize.

Title: Maybe You Should Talk to Someone: A Therapist, Her Therapist, and Our Lives Revealed
Author: Lori Gottlieb
My Review:
I don't believe this book was for me and honestly I'm really disappointed.

Recommended for people in their late 20s onwards as a physical book if you don't mind an unlikeable narrator.

Title: My Dark Vanessa
Author: Kate Elizabeth Russell
My Review:
This is a book about denial, about grief, and about abuse. It is raw and heartfelt, and although the character is unlikeable at times, as the reader continues he/she/they learn what experiences/events might have contributed to the main character's attitude.

Some people might complain about the length, but I think it was justifiable as it really ensured that the reader understood the feelings that the main character was going through throughout the course of her abuse; I think it was necessary to convey what was needed in the book.

Honestly... This book is nearly perfect in my eyes. Well researched, emotionally charged, well-written in a way that made sense given the story.

I would recommend this book to anyone who would not be triggered by it.

Title: The Female of the Species
Author: Mindy McGinnis
My Review:
I did not enjoy this book in the slightest; it was quite disappointing in an audiobook format.

Perhaps I would have enjoyed it more if I had read it on paper, but hindsight is 20/20 I suppose.

Title: Pretty Girls
Author: Karin Slaughter
My Review:
Mhmm mhmm mhmmm. Sweet sweet justice was served to unlikeable characters that you weirdly grow to care about. A few racist comments extraneous to plot were added in the beginning to cement the main characters as unlikeable, which was not appreciated in the slightest however.

If not for the sprinkles of - why author? - in the beginning of the book though, this would be a solid book. I don't think this is a book to go out of your way to read though; if you are interested, go for it but otherwise - eh.

Title: Fun Home: A Family Tragicomic
Author: Alison Bechdel
My Review:
A very thought provoking and honestly inspiring memoir in the form of a graphic novella. Questions are posed throughout this book that stick with you, statements that bring alive the artistic muse living within your tiny pandemic proof birdhouse - it's beautiful in a way that is indescribable. Perhaps it's the fact that I greatly enjoy classical literature and my partner enjoys philosophy that really allowed this book to speak to me, or perhaps it was the honest portrayal that the author provides, as James Joyce did in Ulysses. I can't say for sure.

What I can say is that I would recommend this book, even though it has a particularly interesting perspective on Mr. Antolini's & Holden's relationship in Catcher in the Rye that I respectfully disagree with.

Title: Gwendy's Button Box (The Button Box, #1)
Author: Stephen King
My Review: I am perplexed by this book, as I enjoyed it but the ending left me confused. I want to think there is a deeper meaning to this book, but I genuinely didn’t find any horror aspects or anything more than what could happen when faced with the allure of power. But not even that was truly explored in a satisfying way... and yet I still enjoyed this tremendously; it’s honestly so confusing for me. I think the build up was just so thrilling that I’m still in a a bit of a cloud nine situation because of it but objectively, I don’t know if this book is worth the read. Weird indeed.

Title: Monster, She Wrote: The Women Who Pioneered Horror and Speculative Fiction
Author: Lisa Kröger
My Review:
Started strong but didn't hold my attention for long.

Unfortunately the choice to include recommendation after every page made me lose interest in the actual prose. Why read the prose when I can just jot down new book to read and read that book instead? I wish the authors chose to have the Notes after every chapter and the recommendations at the end.

Nonfiction does this to me, and sadly the biographies for each author were too long for me to keep interest and the prose wasn't exactly my style either.

Overall though, I would still recommend this book for anyone who champions horror, and I may revisit it in the future. As a newb to the horror genre, this book provided many good book recommendations, but may have been a bit much and was not what I expected.
